<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Additional Graph Theory</title>
  <p>
    A <term>digraph</term>
    (or <term>directed graph</term>)
    <m>D</m> consists of a set <m>V</m> of vertices and a set <m>E</m> of
    <term>directed edges</term>
    (or <term>arrows</term>),
    each of which is represented as an ordered pair <m>(u,v)</m>,
    where <m>u,v\in V</m>.
    We say that <m>u</m> is the <term>initial vertex</term>
    and <m>v</m> is the <term>terminal vertex</term>
    of the directed edge <m>(u,v)</m>.
    We write <m>D=(V,E)</m> as we did with undirected graphs.
    The <term>indegree</term> of a vertex <m>v</m> in a digraph,
    denoted <m>{\deg^-(v)}</m>,
    is the number of directed edges that have <m>v</m> as a terminal vertex while the
    <term>outdegree</term> of <m>v</m>,
    denoted <m>{\deg^+(v)}</m>,
    is the number of edges having <m>v</m> as an initial vertex.
  </p>
  <problem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the indegree and outdegree of each vertex in the following graph.
      </p>
