  <p>
    Unfortunately, unlike the situation for Euler circuits,
    there is no known simple necessary and sufficient condition for a Hamilton cycle to exist in a graph.
    We can state some simple cases when one cannot exist,
    and there are some theorems for the existence of a Hamilton cycle,
    but these do not cover all possibilities.
  </p>
  <theorem>
    <title>Dirac's Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>G</m> is a simple graph of order <m>n \ge 3</m> in which <m>\deg(v) \geq n/2</m> for each vertex,
        then <m>G</m> has a Hamilton cycle.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <theorem>
    <title>Ore's Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>G</m> is a simple graph of order <m>n \geq 3</m> in which
        <m>\deg(u) + \deg(v) \geq n</m> for each pair of vertices <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>,
        then <m>G</m> has a Hamilton cycle.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  <problem>
